    <definition xml:id="def-volume-of-a-cone">
        <statement>
            <p>
                A <m>\textbf{cone}</m> is a right pyramid with a circular base
            </p>
            <p>
                In the limit, as the number of faces approaches infinity, the shape is a cone.
            </p>
            <p>
                Play along with the interactive figure below to see how cone is formed from a pyramid.
            </p>
            
            <figure >
                <caption>A cone formed from a pyramid</caption>
                <interactive xml:id="geogebra-volume-of-a-cone" platform="geogebra" width="100%">
                <slate xml:id="Volume-of-a-cone" surface="geogebra" material="rusrttf2" aspect="11:13" >
                    enableShiftDragZoom(true);
                    showResetIcon(true);
                </slate>
                </interactive>
            </figure>
            
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        From your activity, it takes three cones to fill a cylinder with the same base and height. 
        This tells us that the coneâ€™s volume is <m>\textbf{one-third}</m> the volume of the cylinder.
    </p>
    <p>
        Therefore the volume is given by?
        <me>
            \textbf{Volume of a cone} = \frac{1}{3} \pi r^2 h
        </me>
        
    </p>
    <p>
        Where <m>r</m> is the radius of the base and <m>h</m> is the height of the cone.
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Calculate the volume of the cone shown below. (Take <m>\pi=\frac{22}{7}</m>)
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="cone-volume-example" >
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Draw the entire cone with one uniform color
                    \fill[white!40] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.7) -- (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.7) -- cycle;
                    \fill[cyan!40] (-2,0) -- (0,4) -- (2,0) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Draw the base ellipse
                    \draw[thick] (-2,0) arc (180:360:2 and 0.7);
                    \draw[dashed] (2,0) arc (0:180:2 and 0.7);
                    
                    % Draw the cone's sides
                    \draw[thick] (-2,0) -- (0,4);
                    \draw[thick] (2,0) -- (0,4);
                    
                    % Draw the height
                    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (0,4);
                    \node[left] at (1,2) {28 cm};
                    
                    % Draw the radius
                    \draw[dashed] (0,0) -- (2,0);
                    \node[below] at (1,0) {14 cm};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <m>\text{Volume of a cone} = \frac{1}{3} \times \text{Base Area} \times \text{Height}</m>
                <me>
                    = \frac{1}{3} \times \pi r^2 \times h
                </me>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Volume}= \amp \frac{1}{3} \times \pi r^2 \times h </mrow>
                    <mrow>=\amp  \frac{1}{3} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 14^2 \times 28 </mrow>
                    <mrow>=\amp  \frac{1}{3} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 196 \times 28 </mrow>
                    <mrow>=\amp  \frac{1}{3} \times \frac{22}{7} \times 5488 </mrow>
                    <mrow>=\amp  \frac{1}{3} \times 22 \times 784 </mrow>
                    <mrow>=\amp  \frac{17248}{3} </mrow>
                    <mrow>=\amp  5749.33 \text{ cm}^3 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the volume of the cone is <m>{\color{black}5749.33 \text{ cm}^3}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A party hat has the shape of a cone.
                The volume of the hat is <m>462 \, \text{cm}^3</m>. The hat has a perpendicular 
                height of <m>17 \, \text{cm}</m>, find the radius of the base of the hat.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The hat has the following dimensions:
            </p>
            <p>
                Volume of hat = <m>462 \, \text{cm}^3</m>, height = <m>17 \, \text{cm}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Volume of the hat}= \amp \frac{1}{3} \pi r^2 h</mrow>
                    <mrow>462 = \amp \frac{1}{3} \pi r^2 (17)</mrow>
                    <mrow>462 = \amp \frac{22}{21} \times 17 \times  r^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>462 \times 21 = \amp 22  \times 17 \times r^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> 9702= \amp 374 \times r^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> r^2= \amp \frac{9702}{374} </mrow>
                    <mrow> r= \amp \sqrt{\frac{9702}{374}}</mrow>
                    <mrow> r= \amp \sqrt{25.95} </mrow>
                    <mrow> r= \amp 5.5 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the radius of the base of the hat is <m>{\color{black}5.5 \, \text{cm}}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                The figure below shows a model made from two cones.
                Determine the volume of the model. (Take <m>\pi=3.142</m>)
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image >
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Draw rhombus (two joined triangles)
                    \draw [very thick] (0,0) -- (2.5,3.5) -- (5,0) -- (2.5,-3.5) -- cycle;

                    % Draw diagonals
                    \draw[dashed,very thick] (0,0) -- (5,0);
                    \draw[dashed,very thick] (2.5,-3.5) -- (2.5,3.5);

                    % Labels for diagonals
                    \draw[very thick] (2.5,0) -- (2.5,3) node[midway,right]{ 10 cm};
                    \draw[very thick] (2.5,0) -- (2.5,-3) node[midway,right]{ 10 cm};
                    \draw[very thick,dashed] (0,0) -- (2.5,0);
                    \node at (1.25,0.2) { 3.5 cm};
                    \draw[very thick] (2.5,0) -- (5,0);


                    % Draw horizontal ellipse in the middle
                    \draw[thick,blue] (2.5,0) ellipse [x radius=2.5, y radius=0.7];
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The model consists of two cones with the same base radius and height.
            </p>
            <p>
                The height of each cone is <m>10 \, \text{cm}</m> and the radius of the base is <m>3.5 \, \text{cm}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                The volume of one cone is given by the formula:
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Volume} =\amp \frac{1}{3} \pi r^2 h</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{3} \times 3.142 \times (3.5)^2 \times 20</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{3} \times 3.142 \times 12.25 \times 20</mrow>
                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{3} \times 3.142 \times 245</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{769.83}{3}</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 256.61 \, \text{cm}^3</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore, the volume of one cone is <m>{\color{black}256.61 \, \text{cm}^3}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
